Capital gains yield refers to how much the price of an investment changes with respect to its original price. This can be solved by subtracting the dividend yield from the required rate of return for each of the given stocks. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Capital gains yield}&=\text{Rate of return}-\text{Dividend yield}
\end{aligned}$$

Now, in order to get the dividend rate of each of the stocks, we must first determine the price of each stock. To do this, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price}&=\text{Dividend} \times \dfrac{1+\text{Growth Rate}}{\text{Rate of return}-\text{Growth Rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

To solve for the price of Stock Z, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price}&=\dfrac{\text{Dividend}\times(1+\text{Initial growth rate})^\text{Number of years}\times(1+\text{Growth rate after initial}}{\text{Required rate}-\text{Growth rate after initial}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price}&=\dfrac{\$3.75 \times(1+0.20)^2\times(1+0.05)}{0.13-0.05}\\[15 pt]
&=\$70.875
\end{aligned}$$

The price of Stock Z is $\$70.875$.
